31. populo Romano: of course only by those whose sympa- thies were aristocratic.

32. sociis et Latinis: the interests of these were specially threatened by the agrarian legislation of Gracchus. The phrase sociis et Latinis taken together forms the third member in Cicero’s enumeration, as shown by the fact that et is not used between the last two members of an enumeration unless between all the other members. Cicero accordingly means ‘ the allies and (particularly) the Latins‚' these last being an important element of the socii.
